            {
                "text": "Maintain a regular sleep schedule."
            },
            {
                "text": "Before sleeping, mentally repeat: 'Today I will remember my dreams'. It sounds like magic, but neuroscience calls it Prospective Memory. It works!"
            },
            {
                "text": "Avoid screens 1h before sleeping."
            },
            {
                "text": "Write down your dreams as soon as you wake up."
            },
            {
                "text": "Can't switch off? Breathe in through your nose for 4 seconds, hold for 7, and exhale through your mouth for 8. This 'hacks' your vagus nerve and forces the body to relax physically."
            },
            {
                "text": "Expose yourself to natural light as soon as you wake up. Sunlight zeroes melatonin production and sets your internal clock so you feel sleepy at the right time at night."
            },
            {
                "text": "Nightmares are often the brain trying to process difficult emotions from the day. Recording them helps to understand your fears and overcome traumas."
            },
            {
                "text": "Caffeine has a long 'half-life'. That 5PM espresso is still 50% active in your blood at bedtime, preventing you from entering the deep REM sleep where dreams happen."
            }
        ]
